I’ll use **simple ASCII diagrams** so they’re easy to remember and explain.

***

# ✅ JavaScript Prototype Chain — Diagrams & Explanation

***

## 🔹 Core Concept (One‑Line)

> Every JavaScript object has a hidden property called `[[Prototype]]` (`__proto__`) that points to another object, forming a **prototype chain** for property lookup.

***

# 1️⃣ Simple Object → `Object.prototype`

### ✅ Code

```js
const obj = {
  name: "Raja"
};
```

### ✅ Prototype Chain Diagram

    obj
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    null

### ✅ Lookup Flow

```js
obj.toString()
```

1.  JS checks `obj`
2.  Not found
3.  Checks `Object.prototype` ✅
4.  Stops at `null`

📌 **Every object ultimately links to `Object.prototype`**

***

# 2️⃣ Constructor Function Prototype Chain

### ✅ Code

```js
function Person(name) {
  this.name = name;
}

const p1 = new Person("Raja");
```

### ✅ Prototype Chain Diagram

    p1
     ↓ __proto__
    Person.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    null

### ✅ Key Points

*   `p1.__proto__ === Person.prototype`
*   Methods should be added to `Person.prototype`

```js
Person.prototype.greet = function () {
  console.log("Hello");
};
```

✅ Saves memory  
✅ Shared across all instances

***

# 3️⃣ Method Lookup (Very Important for Interviews)

```js
p1.greet();
```

### ✅ Lookup Order

    p1
     → Person.prototype ✅ greet found
     → Object.prototype
     → null

✅ Stops as soon as method is found

***

# 4️⃣ ES6 Class Prototype Chain (Same as Constructor)

### ✅ Code

```js
class Person {
  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
}

const p = new Person();
```

### ✅ Prototype Chain Diagram

    p
     ↓ __proto__
    Person.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    null

📌 **Classes are just syntactic sugar over prototypes**

***

# 5️⃣ Inheritance Prototype Chain (`extends`)

### ✅ Code

```js
class Employee extends Person {
  work() {}
}

const e = new Employee();
```

### ✅ Prototype Chain Diagram

    e
     ↓ __proto__
    Employee.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    Person.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    null

### ✅ Method Resolution Order

    e → Employee.prototype → Person.prototype → Object.prototype

✅ This is **true inheritance** in JavaScript

***

# 6️⃣ `Object.create()` Prototype Chain (Explicit)

### ✅ Code

```js
const parent = {
  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
};

const child = Object.create(parent);
```

### ✅ Diagram

    child
     ↓ __proto__
    parent
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    null

✅ Direct prototype control  
✅ No constructor, no `this`

***

# 7️⃣ Function Objects Prototype Chain (Special Case)

```js
function test() {}
```

### ✅ Diagram

    test
     ↓ __proto__
    Function.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    null

📌 Functions are **objects too**

***

# 8️⃣ Built‑in Objects (Array Example)

```js
const arr = [];
```

### ✅ Diagram

    arr
     ↓ __proto__
    Array.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    null

### ✅ Why this works

```js
arr.push()      // from Array.prototype
arr.toString() // from Object.prototype
```

***

# 🔥 Most Common Interview Diagram (Must Remember)

    instance
     ↓ __proto__
    Constructor.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ↓ __proto__
    null

✅ Applies to:

*   Constructor functions
*   ES6 classes
*   Most JS objects

***

# ✅ Comparison: `prototype` vs `__proto__`

| Term        | Belongs To  | Meaning                 |
| ----------- | ----------- | ----------------------- |
| `prototype` | Constructor | Blueprint for instances |
| `__proto__` | Object      | Points to its prototype |

```js
p.__proto__ === Person.prototype // ✅ true
```

***

# ✅ One‑Line Interview Answer

> The prototype chain is the mechanism by which JavaScript objects inherit properties, where each object links to another via `__proto__` until `Object.prototype` or `null` is reached.

***

# ✅ Why Prototype Chain Matters

*   Inheritance
*   Memory optimization
*   Method reuse
*   Understanding `class` internals
*   Debugging `undefined` methods

