# ✅ JavaScript Prototype — Output‑Based Interview Questions

***

## 🔹 Q1: Basic Prototype Lookup

```js
const obj = {};
console.log(obj.toString());
```

### ✅ Output

    [object Object]

### ✅ Explanation

*   `toString()` is not in `obj`
*   Found in `Object.prototype`
*   Prototype chain:  
    `obj → Object.prototype → null`

***

## 🔹 Q2: Constructor Function Prototype

```js
function Person(name) {
  this.name = name;
}

Person.prototype.greet = function () {
  return "Hello " + this.name;
};

const p = new Person("Raja");
console.log(p.greet());
```

### ✅ Output

    Hello Raja

### ✅ Explanation

*   `greet()` is found on `Person.prototype`
*   `this.name` refers to `p.name`

***

## 🔹 Q3: Shadowing Prototype Property

```js
function User() {}
User.prototype.role = "Admin";

const u1 = new User();
u1.role = "User";

console.log(u1.role);
console.log(User.prototype.role);
```

### ✅ Output

    User
    Admin

### ✅ Explanation

*   Instance property (`u1.role`) shadows prototype property
*   Prototype value remains unchanged

***

## 🔹 Q4: Deleting Instance Property

```js
function Car() {}
Car.prototype.speed = 100;

const car = new Car();
car.speed = 200;

delete car.speed;
console.log(car.speed);
```

### ✅ Output

    100

### ✅ Explanation

*   After deletion, JS looks up prototype chain
*   Finds `speed` on `Car.prototype`

***

## 🔹 Q5: `__proto__` vs `prototype`

```js
function Test() {}

const t = new Test();

console.log(t.__proto__ === Test.prototype);
```

### ✅ Output

    true

### ✅ Explanation

*   `prototype` → property of constructor
*   `__proto__` → internal reference on instance

***

## 🔹 Q6: Prototype Chain Length

```js
const arr = [];
console.log(arr.__proto__.__proto__.__proto__);
```

### ✅ Output

    null

### ✅ Explanation

Prototype chain:

    arr
     → Array.prototype
     → Object.prototype
     → null

***

## 🔹 Q7: Method Lookup Priority

```js
function A() {}
A.prototype.show = function () {
  return "A";
};

function B() {}
B.prototype = Object.create(A.prototype);
B.prototype.show = function () {
  return "B";
};

const obj = new B();
console.log(obj.show());
```

### ✅ Output

    B

### ✅ Explanation

Lookup order:

    obj → B.prototype ✅ → A.prototype → Object.prototype

Closest method wins.

***

## 🔹 Q8: Object.create Prototype

```js
const parent = {
  value: 10
};

const child = Object.create(parent);
child.value = 20;

console.log(child.value);
console.log(parent.value);
```

### ✅ Output

    20
    10

### ✅ Explanation

*   Child has its own `value`
*   Parent untouched

***

## 🔹 Q9: Removing Prototype Method

```js
function Foo() {}
Foo.prototype.test = () => "Hello";

const f = new Foo();
delete Foo.prototype.test;

console.log(f.test);
```

### ✅ Output

    undefined

### ✅ Explanation

*   Method removed from prototype chain
*   No fallback found → `undefined`

***

## 🔹 Q10: `hasOwnProperty` Check

```js
function Item() {}
Item.prototype.price = 100;

const i = new Item();

console.log(i.hasOwnProperty("price"));
console.log("price" in i);
```

### ✅ Output

    false
    true

### ✅ Explanation

*   `hasOwnProperty` → only instance properties
*   `in` → instance + prototype

***

## 🔹 Q11: Function Prototype Special Case

```js
function demo() {}
console.log(typeof demo.__proto__);
```

### ✅ Output

    function

### ✅ Explanation

*   `demo.__proto__ === Function.prototype`
*   Functions inherit from `Function.prototype`

***

## 🔹 Q12: Prototype Overwrite Trap ⚠️

```js
function Test() {}
Test.prototype.x = 10;

const t1 = new Test();

Test.prototype = { x: 20 };

const t2 = new Test();

console.log(t1.x);
console.log(t2.x);
```

### ✅ Output

    10
    20

### ✅ Explanation

*   `t1` references old prototype
*   `t2` references new prototype
*   Prototype reassignment does NOT affect existing instances

***

# ✅ Most Important Interview Takeaways

✅ Prototype lookup is **dynamic**  
✅ Closest property wins  
✅ Instances reference prototype at creation time  
✅ `delete` exposes prototype values  
✅ `Object.create()` gives direct prototype control

***

## ✅ One‑Line Interview Answer

> JavaScript resolves properties by searching the object first, then walking up the prototype chain until it finds the property or reaches `null`.

